SIMPLE: envy
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Envy
<hw>En"vy</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it>
<plw>Envies</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[F. <ets>envie</ets>, L.
<ets>invidia</ets> envious; akin to <ets>invidere</ets> to look askance
at, to look with enmity; <ets>in</ets> against + <ets>videre</ets> to
see. See <er>Vision</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Malice; ill will;
spite.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>If he evade us there,⟦br⟧
Enforce him with his <qex>envy</qex> to the people.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Chagrin, mortification, discontent, or uneasiness at
the sight of another's excellence or good fortune, accompanied with some
degree of hatred and a desire to possess equal advantages; malicious
grudging; -- usually followed by <xex>of</xex>; <as>as, they did this in
<ex>envy</ex> of C⟦ae⟧sar</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Envy</qex> is a repining at the prosperity or good of
another, or anger and displeasure at any good of another which we want,
or any advantage another hath above us.</q> <rj><qau>Ray.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>No bliss⟦br⟧
Enjoyed by us excites his <qex>envy</qex> more.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Envy</qex>, to which the ignoble mind's a slave,⟦br⟧
Is emulation in the learned or brave.</q> <rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Emulation; rivalry.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Such as cleanliness and decency⟦br⟧
Prompt to a virtuous <qex>envy</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Ford.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Public odium; ill repute.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To lay the <qex>envy</qex> of the war upon Cicero.</q> <rj><qau>B.
Jonson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>An object of envious notice or feeling.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>This constitution in former days used to be the <qex>envy</qex> of
the world.</q> <rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Envy</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Envy
<hw>En"vy</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Envied</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Envying</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[F. <ets>envier</ets>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>To feel envy at or towards; to be envious of; to have a
feeling of uneasiness or mortification in regard to (any one), arising
from the sight of another's excellence or good fortune and a longing to
possess it.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A woman does not <qex>envy</qex> a man for his fighting courage,
nor a man a woman for her beauty.</q> <rj><qau>Collier.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Whoever <qex>envies</qex> another confesses his superiority.</q>
<rj><qau>Rambler.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To feel envy on account of; to have a feeling of
grief or repining, with a longing to possess (some excellence or good
fortune of another, or an equal good fortune, etc.); to look with
grudging upon; to begrudge.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I have seen thee fight,⟦br⟧
When I have <qex>envied</qex> thy behavior.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Jeffrey . . . had actually <qex>envied</qex> his friends their
cool mountain breezes.</q> <rj><qau>Froude.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To long after; to desire strongly; to
covet.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Or climb his knee the <qex>envied</qex> kiss to share.</q>
<rj><qau>T. Gray.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To do harm to; to injure; to disparage.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>If I make a lie⟦br⟧
To gain your love and <qex>envy</qex> my best mistress,⟦br⟧
Put me against a wall.</q> <rj><qau>J. Fletcher.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To hate.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Marlowe.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>To emulate.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Envy</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Envy
<hw>En"vy</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To be
filled with envious feelings; to regard anything with grudging and
longing eyes; -- used especially with <xex>at</xex>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Who would <qex>envy</qex> at the prosperity of the wicked?</q>
<rj><qau>Jer. Taylor.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To show malice or ill will; to rail.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> ⟦ldquo⟧He has . . . <xex>envied</xex> against the
people.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Envyned</ent>⟦br⟧
